*Original response below:*

Do you have the freedom to add `export` in front of `class Foo {`?

That way users can say:

    import { Foo } from &quot;./module&quot;;

and then use `Foo` directly:

    function takesFoo(foo: Foo) {

Alternatively, if `Foo` is the only thing exported from module and you want it to be default export, it would make more sense to export it alone, rather than wrapping it in an object:

    export default Foo; 

so users could import it:

    import Foo from &quot;./module&quot;;

The way I think of `default` export is that it makes the most sense if I only have one thing to export, in which case why wrap it in an object? And if I have multiple things to export, I just export them individually so they can be imported with `{ ... }` as needed.

